Observations from categorical univariate counts

  1. There is so much unknown in the poutcome column and it highly skews the distribution. Futher investigation would be needed to understand why the outcome was not recorded. Could it be a mojority were not profiled in the last campaign and are new customers? This column cannot be easily dropped as it explains the outcome of the previous campaign
  2. There is very limited variability in customers who have credit in default. 98% have no defaults. This column would be dropped as it explains no variability in data.
  3. The Target column is also highly skewed. Over 88% didn't subbscribe to the term deposit. Futher multi-variate analysis required.
  4. A high percentage (84%) of customers have NO personal loans. A high skew too.
  5. A majority of the last contact were in the middle third of the year (i.e. may, jun, july, aug) and also in November.

Observations for Months
Most customers were last contacted in the summer months of May,June,July and August and in the Autumn in November.However, the percentage of responses to number of calls we very low.

Moreover for customers with last contact in the months of March, Sept, October, December the subscription rate was quite high. Perhaps there should be emphasis on targeting calls during this months

Summary Conclusion

  1. Regardless of means of communication, the longer the duration then the more likely a customer would subscribe to a term deposit. (when contacting customer via cellullar or telephone, spending a duration of at least 200 seconds results in a higher chance for term deposit subscription)
  2. default is highly skewed with over 98% of customers having no default. column would be dropped from modeling
  3. Contacting via cellular has a slighly higher chance of getting a customer to subscribe
  4. Most customers were last contacted in the summer months of May,June,July and August and in the Autumn in November.However, the percentage of responses to number of calls we very low.
    Moreover for customers with last contact in the months of March, Sept, October, December the subscription rate was quite high. Perhaps there should be emphasis on targeting calls during this months
  5. Generally no strong correlation among the independent variables except for pdays and previous has Pearson's correlation of 0.54
  6. Our target variable is highly skewed. This would affect the accuracy of the model as no doing anything would already suggest an 88% accuracy if we predicted "No" all the time.
  7. independents variables would be binned but not necessarily scaled since decision trees and ensemble techniques are less suceptible to outliers

In [48]:
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# changing values of solver which works with 'l2'
train_score=[]
test_score=[]
recall_scoreArr=[]
precision_scoreArr=[]
f1_scoreArr=[]
solver = ['newton-cg','lbfgs','liblinear','sag','saga']
for i in solver:
    model = LogisticRegression(random_state=r_seed,penalty='l2', solver=i)  # changing values of solver
    model.fit(X_train, y_train) 
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)     
    train_score.append(round(model.score(X_train,y_train),3))
    test_score.append(round(model.score(X_test, y_test),3))
    recall_scoreArr.append(round(recall_score(y_test,y_predict),3))
    precision_scoreArr.append(round(precision_score(y_test,y_predict),3))
    f1_scoreArr.append(round(f1_score(y_test,y_predict),3))
    
print(solver)
print()
print(train_score)
print()
print(test_score)
print('Recall')
print(recall_scoreArr)
print('Precision')
print(precision_scoreArr)
print('F1 Score')
print(f1_scoreArr)

3.3 Model Comparison and Conclusion¶

Confusion matrix meaning

True Positive (observed=1,predicted=1):

Predicted that term deposit should be offered and the customer will subscribe to term deposit.

False Positive (observed=0,predicted=1):

Predicted that term deposit should be offered to customer but unfortunately the customer will not subscribe to term deposit.

True Negative (observed=0,predicted=0):

Predicted that term deposit should not be offered and the customer will not subscribe to term deposit.

False Negative (observed=1,predicted=0):

Predicted that term deposit should not be offered but the customer would have subscribed to the term deposit



Since the bank wants to improve/increase the number of customers who will subscribe to term deposit offer, we want to reduce False Negatives (FN). If FN is high, then it means the bank would not make as much money from the investments derived from the term depoists as we are predicting that customers who would have subscibedto the term deposit wouldn't subscribe to it. Recall is therefore an important metric that we want to optimize (i.e. get as much true positives as possible correctly and reduce FN as much as posible).


Using the table above showing comparison of six techniques. "Decision Tree" (45.86%) and "Bagging" (45.8%) have the highest Recall percentage (with Decison tree being just slightly better) so either could be selected.

However, i would select Bagging because it has a slightly higher F-score, accuracy and precision as compared to Decision Tree.
